I made this for Thanksgiving and again for a dinner party, and it doubled as a delicious table decoration in both instances. I would be a bit cautious about the type of pumpkin you use - of the two times I made, it, the sugar pie pumpkin worked out much better than the larger variety. Also - word to the wise - use your common sense with the amount of salt (i.e more salt if you're using Emmenthal; less if you're using Gruyere or Cheddar)... Oh, and use allllllll the cream (it'll bake off into pure deliciousness).... :)

Rating: 4
This was delicious! I have tried various other main courses for vegetarian friends and family at big meals and had not yet found a dish that did not end up feeling like a side note to the meat. This was not the case here and this dish got rave reviews from everyone at the table, including the carnivores. I used a kabocha squash, as some other reviews indicated, and it was great. For the stuffing I basically stuck to the recipe with addition of some walnuts and while it tasted great, I will add extra bread in the future as it seems to get lost in the rest of the ingredients. However, the best thing about this is how versatile it is. I will definitely make this again, and can't wait to try bread alternatives such as rice or quinoa. Bottom line, if you are looking for a hearty vegetarian main course that doesn't feel somehow less than a meat main does, this is the recipe for you.

