I have made this several times with different ingredients, based on Dorie's suggestions. By far, the family favorite is with cooked (left-over) brown rice and more bacon (6 cooked slices at least). I don't salt the pumpkin at all, since the bacon is salty enough. I also use a really good white cheddar for the cheese, and lots of black pepper. Try using different kinds of pumkin. Our farmer's market is loaded with all kinds, and the growers are great about making suggestions for which kind of pumpkin to try.

Rating: 4
I made this many times in a pumpkin but in late winter early spring, cooked it in a heart-shaped Staub La Cocotte. The first couple of times it came out oily (the pumpkin flesh absorbs the oil). This time it worked perfectly. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. For cooking in the Staub La Cocotte: 4 slices cooked bacon, chopped; 1/2# gruyere; 1/2# stale cranberry walnut bread; 1/3 c dried cherries; 2 large garlic cloves, minced; 3 c choppped arugula; 1/2 large onion, diced; salt and pepper to taste. Combine in large bowl until mixed well. Pack into La Cocotte. Mix 1/2 c heavy cream with 2 pinches nutmeg and pour evenly over mixture. Cover and place in oven. Cook for 45 minutes.

