Wow, I just finished my second helping. I like many others adjusted the recipe to facilitate what I had available, as I live in a small town. I did splurge and purchased the Gruyere and it complimented the recipe. I used a Mahagany brown rice, fresh spinach, diced ham, sauted onion, dried chives and thyme, golder raisins, and reduced the cream. I found my version to be moist. Also, my pumpkin which I cooked on a cookie sheet would have been very easily plated. Can't wait till I use this recipe for a dinner party. Also, don't be afraid to experiment with alternative ingredients, as I feel this recipe is extremely flexible and versatile

Rating: 4
most excellent! I made this recipe pretty much as written with the exception of using a buttercup squash instead of a pumpkin (couldnt find any suitable pumpkins), and I used a tsp of dried thyme instead of fresh. I used a mixed Gruyere, Fontina & sharp cheddar. baked it in a glass pie pan with no issues.. straight from oven to table, parchment unnecessary, and the presentation factor still intact. The squash being a bit smaller, took a tad less time to bake. With it's deep green shell and bright orange flesh, I dare say it was prettier than a pumpkin would have been. I'm not a fan of stuffing, but what's not to like about cheese and bacon? very tasty and quite beautiful. Will make this instead of stuffing for Thanksgiving!

