Rating: 4
This recipe demands you to be inspired. I happened to have a 3lb pumpkin sitting around (what are the chances) but I basically just used what I had in the kitchen for the filling. 1c cooked and seasoned brown rice, lots of parmesan, chopped fresh kale, chopped pepperoni, minced garlic and a little heavy cream fit perfectly inside. Since I didn't really have to worry about cooking my stuffing, I baked on 375 for an hour and the pumpkin was soft, attractive and delicious! The rice was creamy, the kale and garlic were nicely cooked, and the whole thing really did look and taste great! Better yet prep time was quick and easy. Looking forward to playing around with this recipe, next time maybe more cheese and I will better salt the inside of the pumpkin. I'm a fan.

Rating: 4
Each year for Octoberfest I bake this on cookie sheet and everyone raves about it! My variation include sauteing 2 yellow onions w/12 oz mushrooms and add3 oz truffle paste. Add that mixture to 3 cups mascarpone, 12 oz Emmenthaller 4 oz Parmesan and 3 eggs. I use 8 slices of day old bread tossed w/ butter until crisp. I layer the cheese/mushroom mixture then the bread crumbs and repeat. Don't worry if the stuffing doesn't fill the cavity---it all works out. Bake on 375 for 11/2hrs. Perfect every time! and a beautiful deep orange color--a perfect centerpiece.

Rating: 4
This was delicious and pretty filling. I'd be happy with it as a main course; it's festive and very flavorful. I used crisp bacon, some Rembrandt gouda, red onion that I sauteed in a bit of bacon grease, some fresh chopped garlic and rosemary, and lots of dried thyme and black pepper. Instead of cream, I used fat-free half&half (I know!), because that's what I had on hand. The whole thing was aromatic, rich-tasting, and very yummy. I bet it would be wonderful with a sage sausage in place of the bacon! I just had this as a weeknight supper, but it would be delicious with a good fall salad, a glass of wine, and some apple crisp for dessert. Who needs a turkey indeed?

Rating: 4
This is delicious! The flavor of the gruyere cheese and the pumpkin compliment each other wonderfully, and the scallions and thyme add a special touch. This recipe is a great reason to splurge on the cheese; the nice gruyere I bought from Whole Foods really stood out. A couple recommendations: rub the inside of the pumpkin with kosher salt before you stuff it so that the flesh will have more flavor. Toasting the bread with a bit of olive oil is also a nice touch. I did find that the pumpkin needed another half hour in the oven to become truly tender, but that may be because I had a larger one than the recipe called for. Go ahead and fill the pumpkin all the way to the brim - the cheese cubes melt as it cooks, so it will be less full when it is done. If you end up with leftover pumpkin at the end of the night, you can puree it with a little chicken stock or butter and use it like canned pumpkin.

